1
00:02:26,012 --> 00:02:27,946
Mr. Adams!

2
00:02:29,482 --> 00:02:32,246
Mr. Adams!

3
00:02:32,318 --> 00:02:34,684
Mr. Adams!

4
00:02:34,754 --> 00:02:39,487
There you are.
Didn't you hear me call you, Mr. Adams?

5
00:02:39,559 --> 00:02:43,757
You could've shouted down something,
saved me climbing up four flights.

6
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:47,129
A man that likes to talk
as much as you do, I'd think...

7
00:02:48,968 --> 00:02:51,994
What do you keep coming
up here for, Mr. Adams?

8
00:02:52,071 --> 00:02:54,596
Afraid someone's
going to steal our bell?

9
00:02:55,675 --> 00:02:57,609
Well, don't worry.

10
00:02:57,677 --> 00:03:01,169
Been here more than 14 years
and ain't been carried off once.

11
00:03:04,450 --> 00:03:07,942
Better get yourself
back down to Congress, Mr. Adams.

12
00:03:08,021 --> 00:03:09,989
Getting ready to vote,
and they said...

13
00:03:10,056 --> 00:03:12,024
they couldn't settle
such an important question...

14
00:03:12,091 --> 00:03:14,457
without Massachusetts
being there.

15
00:03:15,929 --> 00:03:18,261
I can just imagine.

16
00:03:22,435 --> 00:03:27,304
All right, what burning issue
are we voting on this time?

17
00:03:27,373 --> 00:03:31,309
On whether or not to grant
General Washington's request...

18
00:03:31,377 --> 00:03:34,710
that all members of the Rhode Island
militia be required...

19
00:03:34,781 --> 00:03:37,045
to wear matching uniforms.

20
00:03:38,284 --> 00:03:40,275
Oh, good God.

21
00:04:17,357 --> 00:04:21,726
I have come to the conclusion
that one useless man...

22
00:04:21,794 --> 00:04:24,160
is called a disgrace...

23
00:04:24,230 --> 00:04:28,030
that two are called
a law firm...

24
00:04:28,101 --> 00:04:32,595
and that three or more
become a Congress.

25
00:04:32,672 --> 00:04:36,164
And by God,
I have had this Congress.

26
00:04:36,242 --> 00:04:39,302
For ten years,
King George and his parliament...

27
00:04:39,379 --> 00:04:43,782
have gulled, cullied and diddled these
colonies with their illegal taxes...

28
00:04:43,850 --> 00:04:48,082
Stamp Acts, Townshend Acts,
Sugar Acts, Tea Acts.

29
00:04:48,154 --> 00:04:50,679
And when we dared
stand up like men...

30
00:04:50,757 --> 00:04:53,851
they have stopped our trade,
seized our ships...

31
00:04:53,926 --> 00:04:56,827
blockaded our ports,
burned our towns...

32
00:04:56,896 --> 00:04:59,262
and spilled our blood.

33
00:04:59,332 --> 00:05:04,827
And still this Congress refuses to grant
any of my proposals on independence...

34
00:05:04,904 --> 00:05:08,237
even so much as the courtesy
of open debate.

35
00:05:08,308 --> 00:05:11,573
Good God, what in the hell
are you waiting for?

36
00:05:12,211 --> 00:05:15,544
<i>Sit down, John</i>
<i>Sit down, John</i>

37
00:05:15,615 --> 00:05:19,244
- Thomas, for God's sake, listen to me.
- <i>For God's sake, John, sit down</i>

38
00:05:19,319 --> 00:05:21,253
- <i>Sit down, John</i>
- I've had enough of you.

39
00:05:21,321 --> 00:05:25,257
<i>Sit down, John</i>
<i>For God's sake, John, sit down</i>

40
00:05:25,325 --> 00:05:27,259
- Now, listen...
- <i>Why not open up a window</i>

41
00:05:27,327 --> 00:05:30,319
- Listen to me and forget the window.
- <i>It's 90 degrees</i>

42
00:05:30,396 --> 00:05:32,193
<i>Have mercy, John, please</i>

43
00:05:32,265 --> 00:05:34,597
<i>It's hot as hell</i>
<i>in Philadelphia</i>

44
00:05:34,667 --> 00:05:37,158
<i>Someone ought</i>
<i>to open up a window</i>

45
00:05:37,236 --> 00:05:39,727
<i>I say vote yes</i>

46
00:05:39,806 --> 00:05:41,637
<i>Vote yes</i>

47
