71
00:06:43,836 --> 00:06:46,361
<i>Will someone shut that man up</i>

72
00:06:46,439 --> 00:06:48,031
Never!

73
00:06:49,108 --> 00:06:51,099
Never!

74
00:06:55,681 --> 00:06:57,808
Dear God.

75
00:06:57,884 --> 00:07:02,446
For one solid year they have
been sitting here a whole year...

76
00:07:02,522 --> 00:07:04,752
doing nothing.

77
00:07:04,824 --> 00:07:10,285
<i>I do believe you've laid a curse</i>
<i>on North America</i>

78
00:07:10,363 --> 00:07:15,266
<i>A curse that we here now rehearse</i>
<i>in Philadelphia</i>

79
00:07:16,335 --> 00:07:18,565
<i>A second flood</i>
<i>a simple famine</i>

80
00:07:18,638 --> 00:07:20,606
<i>Plagues of locusts</i>
<i>everywhere</i>

81
00:07:20,673 --> 00:07:24,734
<i>Or a cataclysmic earthquake</i>
<i>I'd accept with some despair</i>

82
00:07:24,811 --> 00:07:28,440
<i>But no</i>
<i>you've sent us Congress</i>

83
00:07:28,514 --> 00:07:32,814
<i>Good God, sir, was that fair</i>

84
00:07:34,153 --> 00:07:37,054
<i>You see, we piddle</i>
<i>twiddle and resolve</i>

85
00:07:37,123 --> 00:07:39,057
<i>Not one damn thing</i>
<i>do we solve</i>

86
00:07:39,125 --> 00:07:41,150
<i>Piddle, twiddle and resolve</i>

87
00:07:41,227 --> 00:07:42,990
<i>Nothing's ever solved</i>

88
00:07:43,062 --> 00:07:46,793
<i>In foul, fetid, fuming</i>
<i>foggy, filthy</i>

89
00:07:46,866 --> 00:07:49,266
<i>Philadelphia</i>

90
00:07:49,335 --> 00:07:53,169
<i>Someone ought</i>
<i>to open up a window</i>

91
00:07:53,239 --> 00:07:56,436
- Oh, good God.
- <i>John, John</i>

92
00:07:56,509 --> 00:08:01,606
<i>Is that you carrying on, John</i>

93
00:08:01,681 --> 00:08:06,209
Oh, Abigail, Abigail, I have such
a desire to knock heads together.

94
00:08:06,285 --> 00:08:08,810
<i>Then why in heaven's name</i>
<i>do you stay there?</i>

95
00:08:08,888 --> 00:08:12,346
<i>Come home to Boston, John.</i>
<i>It's only 300 miles.</i>

96
00:08:12,425 --> 00:08:15,019
<i>If you left tonight,</i>
<i>you could be here in only eight days.</i>

97
00:08:15,094 --> 00:08:17,028
<i>How can I do that, Abigail?</i>

98
00:08:17,096 --> 00:08:20,623
<i>I'm no further along now</i>
<i>than I was when I first came here.</i>

99
00:08:20,700 --> 00:08:22,895
I know, my dearest. I know.

100
00:08:22,969 --> 00:08:25,767
But that's because you make
everything so complicated.

101
00:08:25,838 --> 00:08:27,772
It's all quite simple, really.

102
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:30,934
<i>Just tell the Congress</i>
<i>to declare</i>

103
00:08:31,010 --> 00:08:34,605
<i>Independency</i>

104
00:08:34,680 --> 00:08:36,875
<i>Then sign your name</i>
<i>get out of there</i>

105
00:08:36,949 --> 00:08:40,544
<i>And hurry home to me</i>

106
00:08:40,620 --> 00:08:43,054
<i>Our children</i>
<i>all have dysentery</i>

107
00:08:43,122 --> 00:08:45,454
<i>Little Tom</i>
<i>keeps turning blue</i>

108
00:08:45,525 --> 00:08:49,655
<i>Little Abby has the measles</i>
<i>and I'm coming down with flu</i>

109
00:08:49,729 --> 00:08:52,892
<i>They say we may get smallpox</i>

110
00:08:52,965 --> 00:08:55,695
Madam, what else is new?

111
00:08:58,838 --> 00:09:00,863
Abigail, in my last letter,
I wrote you...

112
00:09:00,940 --> 00:09:05,536
that the king had collected 12,000
German mercenaries to send against us.

113
00:09:05,611 --> 00:09:10,105
I asked you to organize the ladies
to make saltpeter for gunpowder.

114
00:09:10,182 --> 00:09:13,117
- Now, have you done as I asked?
- No, John, I have not.

115
00:09:13,185 --> 00:09:14,743
Well, why have you not?

116
00:09:14,820 --> 00:09:18,085
Because you neglected to tell us
how saltpeter is made.

117
00:09:18,157 --> 00:09:21,991
By treating sodium nitrate
with potassium chloride, of course.

118
00:09:22,061 --> 00:09:24,621
- Oh, yes, of course.
- Will it be done, then?

119
00:09:24,697 --> 00:09:27,598
John, I'm afraid we have
a more urgent problem.

120
00:09:27,667 --> 00:09:29,259
More urgent, madam?

121
00:09:29,335 --> 00:09:35,672
<i>There's one thing every woman's missed</i>
<i>in Massachusetts Bay</i>

122
00:09:35,741 --> 00:09:38,403
<i>Don't smirk at me</i>
<i>you egotist</i>

123
00:09:38,477 --> 00:09:42,243
<i>Pay heed to what I say</i>

124
00:09:42,315 --> 00:09:46,684
<i>We've gone from Framingham to Boston</i>
<i>and we cannot find a pin</i>

125
00:09:47,486 --> 00:09:51,320
'<i>'Don't you know there's a war on"</i>
<i>says the tradesman with a grin</i>

126
00:09:51,390 --> 00:09:55,759
<i>Well, we will</i>
<i>not make saltpeter</i>

127
00:09:55,828 --> 00:10:00,231
<i>Until you send us pins</i>

128
00:10:00,299 --> 00:10:02,494
Pins, madam? Saltpeter.

129
00:10:02,568 --> 00:10:04,468
- Pins.
- Saltpeter.

130
00:10:04,537 --> 00:10:06,562
- Pins.
- Saltpeter.

131
00:10:06,639 --> 00:10:08,004
- Pins.
- Saltpeter.

132
00:10:08,074 --> 00:10:10,634
- Pins. Pins. Pins.
- 'Peter. 'Peter. 'Peter.

133
00:10:15,915 --> 00:10:17,849
Done, madam, done.

134
00:10:17,917 --> 00:10:20,579
Done, John.

135
00:10:20,653 --> 00:10:24,180
- Hurry home, John.
- As soon as I'm able.

136
00:10:24,256 --> 00:10:26,190
Don't stop writing.
It's all I have.

137
00:10:26,258 --> 00:10:28,453
Every day, my dearest friend.

138
00:10:31,764 --> 00:10:34,096
<i>Till then</i>

139
00:10:34,166 --> 00:10:36,862
<i>Till then</i>

140
00:10:36,936 --> 00:10:40,099
<i>I am</i>

141
00:10:40,172 --> 00:10:43,573
<i>As I ever was</i>

142
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:48,273
<i>And ever shall be</i>

143
00:10:48,347 --> 00:10:50,577
<i>Yours</i>

144
00:10:50,650 --> 00:10:52,675
<i>Yours</i>

145
00:10:52,752 --> 00:10:55,220
<i>Yours</i>

146
00:10:55,287 --> 00:10:57,448
<i>Yours</i>

147
00:10:57,523 --> 00:11:00,617
<i>Yours</i>

148
00:11:00,693 --> 00:11:03,924
<i>Saltpeter</i>

149
00:11:03,996 --> 00:11:07,762
<i>John</i>

150
00:11:07,833 --> 00:11:09,425
<i>Pins</i>

151
00:11:11,003 --> 00:11:16,134
<i>Abigail</i>

152
00:11:16,208 --> 00:11:18,733
<i>For God's sake, John</i>

153
00:11:18,811 --> 00:11:20,745
<i>Sit down</i>

154
00:11:35,327 --> 00:11:36,885
Franklin!

155
00:11:39,198 --> 00:11:40,631
Franklin!

156
00:11:42,301 --> 00:11:44,235
Where in hell are you?

157
00:11:46,772 --> 00:11:51,436
I see you hiding behind that tree.
It won't do you any good.

158
00:11:52,578 --> 00:11:55,411
Damn it, this is no time
for playing games.

159
00:11:57,016 --> 00:12:00,417
Franklin, I have been looking
everywhere for you.

160
00:12:00,486 --> 00:12:02,613
Where in God's name
have you been?

161
00:12:02,688 --> 00:12:05,714
Right here, John,
being preserved for posterity.

162
00:12:05,791 --> 00:12:08,089
Do you like it?

163
00:12:11,430 --> 00:12:14,456
- It stinks.
- As ever, the soul of tact.

164
00:12:14,533 --> 00:12:18,663
- Well, the man's no Botticelli.
- And the subject's no Venus.

165
00:12:18,738 --> 00:12:20,968
Where were you last night
when I needed you?

166
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:22,974
You should have heard
what I suffered in there.

167
00:12:23,042 --> 00:12:26,307
I heard, all right,
along with the rest of Philadelphia.

168
00:12:26,378 --> 00:12:28,312
Lord, your voice
is piercing, John.

169
00:12:28,380 --> 00:12:31,406
Well, I wish to heaven
my arguments were.

170
00:12:31,484 --> 00:12:34,851
My God, Franklin, when are they
going to make up their minds?

171
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:36,945
With one hand
they can raise an army

172
00:12:37,022 --> 00:12:40,981
dispatch one of their own to lead it
and cheer the news from Bunker's Hill...

173
00:12:41,060 --> 00:12:43,927
and with the other,
they wave the olive branch...

174
00:12:43,996 --> 00:12:46,965
begging the king for a happy
and permanent reconciliation.

175
00:12:47,032 --> 00:12:49,694
Fat George has declared us
in rebellion.

176
00:12:49,769 --> 00:12:52,704
- Why in bloody hell can't they?
- John, really.

177
00:12:52,772 --> 00:12:54,831
You talk as if independence
were the rule.

178
00:12:54,907 --> 00:12:56,841
It's never been done before.

179
00:12:56,909 --> 00:13:00,003
No colony has ever broken from the
parent stem in the history of the world.

180
00:13:00,079 --> 00:13:03,014
Damn it, Franklin,
you make us sound treasonous.

181
00:13:03,082 --> 00:13:06,916
Do I? Treason, eh?

182
00:13:06,986 --> 00:13:09,511
"Treason is a charge
invented by winners...

183
00:13:09,588 --> 00:13:11,522
as an excuse
for hanging the losers."

184
00:13:11,590 --> 00:13:14,821
I have more to do than stand here
listening to you quote yourself.

185
00:13:14,894 --> 00:13:17,158
No, that was a new one.

186
00:13:17,229 --> 00:13:19,493
Damn it, Franklin,
we're at war.

187
00:13:19,565 --> 00:13:21,533
To defend ourselves,
nothing more.

188
00:13:21,600 --> 00:13:23,932
We expressed our displeasure,
the English moved against us...

189
00:13:24,003 --> 00:13:25,937
and we in turn have resisted.

190
00:13:26,005 --> 00:13:28,633
Now our fellow congressmen
want to effect a reconciliation...

191
00:13:28,707 --> 00:13:31,403
- before it becomes a war.
- Reconciliation, my ass.

192
00:13:31,477 --> 00:13:33,604
The people want independence.

193
00:13:33,679 --> 00:13:35,613
The people have read
Mr. Paine's "Common Sense."

194
00:13:35,681 --> 00:13:39,447
- I doubt very much Congress has.
- That's true.

195
00:13:39,518 --> 00:13:41,452
John, why don't you give it up?

196
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:45,149
Nobody listens to you.
You're obnoxious and disliked.

197
00:13:45,224 --> 00:13:48,682
I'm not promoting John Adams.
I'm promoting independence.

198
00:13:48,761 --> 00:13:51,025
Evidently, they cannot
help connecting the two.

199
00:13:51,096 --> 00:13:53,462
Even your own cousin.

200
00:13:53,532 --> 00:13:56,000
And if Sam Adams can't put up
with you, nobody can.

201
00:13:57,570 --> 00:13:59,504
You're getting at something.

202
00:14:00,673 --> 00:14:02,538
How can you tell?

203
00:14:02,608 --> 00:14:06,738
All right, out with it, Franklin.
What new intrigue are you cooking up?

204
00:14:06,812 --> 00:14:10,646
Let someone else
in Congress propose.

205
00:14:10,716 --> 00:14:12,149
Never!

206
00:14:19,658 --> 00:14:21,922
Why? Who did you have in mind?

207
00:14:21,994 --> 00:14:25,828
I don't know.
I really haven't given it much thought.

208
00:14:26,498 --> 00:14:29,331
You sent for me, Benjamin?

209
00:14:29,401 --> 00:14:32,598
- Never.
- Hello, Johnny!

210
00:14:32,671 --> 00:14:33,660
Richard.

211
00:14:33,739 --> 00:14:36,606
Johnny and I need some advice.

212
00:14:36,675 --> 00:14:40,076
- If it's mine to give, it's yours.
- Thank you, Richard.

213
00:14:40,145 --> 00:14:43,637
The cause that we support
has come to a complete standstill.

214
00:14:43,716 --> 00:14:45,650
- Why do you suppose that is?
- Simple.

215
00:14:45,718 --> 00:14:48,312
- Johnny here is obnoxious and disliked.
- That's true.

216
00:14:48,387 --> 00:14:50,321
What's the solution, I wonder?

217
00:14:52,424 --> 00:14:55,018
Get somebody else
in Congress to propose.

218
00:14:55,094 --> 00:14:58,063
Oh, Richard, that's brilliant.
Wasn't that brilliant, John?

219
00:14:58,130 --> 00:15:01,224
- Brilliant.
- The question remains who can it be.

220
00:15:01,300 --> 00:15:03,393
The man that we need
must belong to a delegation...

221
00:15:03,469 --> 00:15:05,437
publicly committed
to support independence.

222
00:15:05,504 --> 00:15:08,098
At the present time, only Massachusetts,
New Hampshire and Delaware...

223
00:15:08,173 --> 00:15:11,370
- have declared our way.
- And Virginia. Don't forget Virginia.

224
00:15:11,443 --> 00:15:13,377
Richard, I haven't.
How could I?

225
00:15:13,445 --> 00:15:16,312
But strictly speaking, while Virginia's
views on independence are well known...

226
00:15:16,382 --> 00:15:19,374
your legislature in Williamsburg
has never formerly authorized...

227
00:15:19,451 --> 00:15:22,318
its delegation here in Congress
to support the cause.

